WEBVTT

00:51.842 --> 00:55.366
Sugar Creek family, it is so good to be with you again this Sunday morning.

00:55.386 --> 01:00.912
I want to welcome all of you at Missouri City, our Richmond Rosenberg family, all of you online, and everyone right here at Sugar.

01:00.932 --> 01:07.159
I'm gonna give yourselves a hand for being here, showing up, and worshiping, leading in, and worship with us.

01:07.840 --> 01:13.406
Now this is the last Sunday of July, which means one, Pastor Mark will be back next week, that's good.

01:14.047 --> 01:18.612
And second of all, that means we're only 39 days away from the start of NFL season.

01:19.633 --> 01:20.594
Yes, sir, come on.

01:21.090 --> 01:28.542
For all you football fans, I know we're in this law of a season and we're just a few days away.

01:28.602 --> 01:39.639
So I want to begin as a source of encouragement to you with a sports analogy or illustration that I heard a long time ago that actually connects with the topic of politics that we are talking about today.

01:40.560 --> 01:49.234
When you watch a football team, you might think that there is only two teams on the field, but there are actually three teams on the field.

01:49.762 --> 01:53.086
Obviously, you've got the two that are playing against each other.

01:53.106 --> 01:56.649
They're clashing each other because they're both trying to win.

01:56.689 --> 02:07.761
They're moving the ball down the field as far as they can into their end zone and in the process there is chaos, there is commotion, there's a lot of back and forth and guess what?

02:08.041 --> 02:13.928
The more chaos and commotion there is, the more the fans love it because no one wants to watch a boring game that's a blowout.

02:13.948 --> 02:16.050
We find it interesting.

02:16.226 --> 02:20.031
when there are surprises and twists and turns within a game.

02:20.051 --> 02:27.119
The third team on the field is the refs, the officials.

02:27.660 --> 02:45.842
This team that represents the NFL organization located in New York City now has sent this group of referees as delegates, as ambassadors of the organization to serve as agents that would govern the game.

02:45.954 --> 02:52.462
that would help bring order and keep people in alignment with a book called the rule book.

02:53.384 --> 03:02.375
The refs don't get to change the rules, they have to simply abide by the rules and call both teams into accountability according to the NFL rules.

03:03.256 --> 03:13.810
Now, how absurd would it be if the refs who are not of the field but on those field, if they begin to take off their black and white uniforms?

03:14.562 --> 03:19.529
and put on the uniforms of one of the two teams that are playing in this game.

03:20.130 --> 03:20.931
That would be crazy.

03:21.752 --> 03:33.428
Imagine, on opening day, I think it's September 5th or something, that the Ravens are playing the Kansas City Chiefs, and some of the refs begin to put on the jerseys of the Chiefs, and others put on the Ravens jersey.

03:34.129 --> 03:43.762
But that's crazy and lunicle, because in the moment they do, they lose the ability to govern the game, to lead,

03:43.874 --> 03:44.715
as they're called to.

03:46.496 --> 03:54.164
In the world of politics, there are gonna be teams of people arguing, fighting, and clashing with each other.

03:55.225 --> 04:03.532
Political parties who both have the goal of winning, advancing their agenda as far as they can.

04:03.853 --> 04:04.373
And guess what?

04:04.894 --> 04:06.435
The world loves commotion.

04:07.476 --> 04:09.718
Chaos makes the conversation go viral.

04:10.539 --> 04:13.842
News outlets thrive off of disorder.

04:14.626 --> 04:17.789
But there is a third team on the field.

04:18.570 --> 04:21.212
A third team that's on the field, but not of the field.

04:21.673 --> 04:23.635
It's the church of Jesus Christ.

04:24.275 --> 04:24.555
Amen.

04:24.816 --> 04:27.558
It's you and I, believers of Jesus.

04:28.499 --> 04:36.087
When Jesus ascended to heaven, in a sense, the headquarters, his followers became his ambassadors.

04:37.148 --> 04:43.954
They became representatives on planet earth who have his word, both in their hand and in their heart.

04:44.578 --> 04:55.489
They became a people who were filled with his spirit, sent on mission to achieve his agenda on the world, to carry out his purpose on the world.

04:55.529 --> 05:04.298
Because that means, friends, that we are kingdom citizens first, and party participants second.

05:05.519 --> 05:09.483
We are kingdom citizens first, and party participants second.

05:09.523 --> 05:12.146
We are called to be salt and light to the earth.

05:12.610 --> 05:20.959
Peace make us a holy priest unto God here on earth, kingdom, citizens first, and party participants second.

05:21.699 --> 05:25.203
Now that doesn't mean that we don't engage in politics because we should.

05:26.224 --> 05:31.870
It doesn't mean that we don't run for office or be active as God calls us to, we ought to be.

05:33.171 --> 05:39.858
What it means is in all of our political engagement, we never take off our kingdom jersey.

05:40.674 --> 05:57.782
We never remove our primary identity as being followers of Jesus and citizens of his kingdom because the moment we do, we lose our ability and our calling and our mission to represent Jesus as we ought to.

05:57.802 --> 06:07.378
So when people see you, what they should recognize first and foremost is not your political affiliation as much as they might matter to you.

06:07.874 --> 06:19.827
When they see you and when they see me, what they should see and say is what Peter said in 1 Peter chapter 2 verse 9 when he said this, but you and that you was plural.

06:19.887 --> 06:37.426
If he was a Texan, he would say, y'all are a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, God's special possession so that you may declare the praises of him who called you out of darkness

06:37.570 --> 06:39.372
into his wonderful life.

06:39.532 --> 06:46.298
How many people are here on a Sunday morning to declare the praises of God who called us out of darkness into his marvelous life?

06:46.359 --> 06:48.741
Come on, let's give Jesus a praise for that.

06:51.283 --> 06:54.006
Peter says, who you are at your core.

06:55.407 --> 06:57.249
A chosen people, that's who you are.

06:57.269 --> 07:03.195
A royal priesthood, God's special price possession.

07:03.515 --> 07:04.816
That's who you are.

07:05.257 --> 07:06.418
Never forget.

07:06.978 --> 07:09.542
your kingdom identity in the world.

07:11.885 --> 07:15.691
Last week, we talked about the way of Jesus, which is the way of the cross.

07:17.233 --> 07:22.160
And the way of the cross quickly in the early church became the way of the church.

07:23.983 --> 07:31.794
While the world contended for the way of Barabbas, one fueled by hatred and revenge, marked by greed and tribalism,

07:32.258 --> 07:36.725
winning at whatever cost, running over whoever was necessary to advance their agenda.

07:37.606 --> 07:42.153
The church, the early church, lived by a whole different set of rules.

07:43.154 --> 07:46.579
It's as if they had a different playbook they lived by.

07:47.460 --> 07:52.528
In fact, Rodney Stark is a historian and sociologist out of Baylor.

07:52.548 --> 07:56.754
In 1996, he wrote a book called The Rise of Christianity.

07:57.378 --> 08:06.652
in which he investigated how did this marginalized, obscure, small, even handful of people on resurrection morning?

08:07.113 --> 08:15.285
How did they become the major dominant force in Western world just within a few centuries?

08:16.267 --> 08:26.322
Rodney was not a Christian when he wrote this book, but as he investigated the church and the message of Jesus and the life of Jesus, he gave his heart to God because he couldn't

08:26.786 --> 08:32.012
deny the impact of the person and message of Jesus in the world.

08:33.213 --> 08:35.936
And in this book, Rodney Stark, he wrote it like this.

08:36.316 --> 08:49.971
He said, Christianity revitalized life in the Greco-Roman world in the cities by providing new norms and new kinds of social relationships, able to cope with many urgent problems.

08:50.752 --> 08:53.575
The cities filled with homeless and impoverished.

08:54.336 --> 08:56.018
Christianity offered charity

08:56.578 --> 08:57.459
as well as hope.

08:58.140 --> 09:05.827
To cities filled with newcomers and strangers, Christianity offered an immediate basis for attachment.

09:06.468 --> 09:12.394
To cities filled with orphans and widows, Christianity provided a new and expanded sense of family.

09:13.234 --> 09:22.363
To cities torn by violent ethnic strife, Christianity offered a new basis for social solidarity.

09:23.144 --> 09:24.946
And to cities filled with epidemics

09:25.026 --> 09:26.128
fires and earthquakes.

09:26.488 --> 09:28.591
Christianity offered nursing services.

09:29.633 --> 09:42.732
I believe it was the religion's particular doctrines that permitted Christianity to be among the most sweeping and successful revitalization movements in history.

09:44.054 --> 09:46.898
And listen to this, he said, it was the way these

09:47.042 --> 09:48.905
doctrines took on flesh.

09:49.265 --> 09:56.115
Mind you, this is before we have the 66 books of the Bible, perfectly canonized and ordered.

09:56.856 --> 10:15.282
But already in the first century, there are doctrines taught by Jesus and the apostles began to take on flesh and the way they directed organizational actions and individual behavior led to the rise of Christianity.

10:16.386 --> 10:35.612
Rodney's saying, just within the first few centuries, immediately after Jesus ascended, the Christians established new norms that the world had never seen, new kinds of relationships that the world had yet to experience, their doctrines.

10:35.632 --> 10:38.616
They didn't just remain in the theological category up in a library.

10:38.957 --> 10:40.539
It wasn't just a mental ascent.

10:41.140 --> 10:42.962
They took on flesh.

10:43.906 --> 10:51.575
And people lived differently because of what they believed about Jesus and because of what Jesus did.

10:52.236 --> 10:55.540
And this changed the world.

10:57.502 --> 11:02.828
Let me give you a few examples of how the Christians lived drastically different in the first century Roman Empire.

11:03.329 --> 11:06.293
For starting, Romans believed in many gods.

11:07.114 --> 11:10.898
Caesar and emperor, they declared themselves as gods.

11:11.682 --> 11:14.907
But Christians says, no, no, there's only one Lord in Savior.

11:14.947 --> 11:18.032
His name is Jesus Christ and we will worship none other.

11:18.092 --> 11:22.459
And they paid a tremendous price for their allegiance to Jesus.

11:23.701 --> 11:26.325
Rome was built off of segregation and classism.

11:27.527 --> 11:32.835
But Christians saw between every ethnicity and race, equality and unity.

11:33.516 --> 11:37.202
And so there's no difference between Jew and Greek, slave and free.

11:37.282 --> 11:39.986
We are one in Christ.

11:41.122 --> 11:45.388
First century Roman Empire looked down on women, treated them as mere property.

11:46.329 --> 11:50.995
But the Christian says, no, no, no, men and women are equally made in God's image.

11:51.015 --> 11:55.841
They have equal worth, the dignity and value were won in Christ.

11:57.223 --> 12:04.733
The virtues of the Roman Empire esteemed were power, greed, materialism, wealth, pride.

12:06.275 --> 12:08.338
But the Christians embodied humility.

12:08.706 --> 12:11.609
service, sacrifice, and generosity.

12:12.730 --> 12:20.739
What was a common practice in first century was both abortion and infanticide, where children were left on the streets to die on purpose.

12:22.240 --> 12:29.188
Procricians believed in the sanctity of all human life, from conception on, from the womb to the tomb.

12:29.208 --> 12:35.314
They held on to the fact that every child was made in God's image and therefore mattered.

12:37.826 --> 12:53.293
The Roman Empire allowed for a variety of sexual practices to be absolutely normal in their day, from extra merit affairs to concubines, to temporal prostitution, and same-sex practices that you find, especially in the Roman upper class.

12:54.876 --> 13:00.786
But Christians, many historians said, led the first sexual revolution the world had ever seen.

13:01.346 --> 13:08.014
a sexual revolution centered on purity and singleness and faithfulness in marriage.

13:09.176 --> 13:11.138
And this was radical in first century.

13:11.919 --> 13:20.089
They said all sexual relationships had to be consensual and covenantal in the confines of marriage that God defined as man and woman.

13:20.349 --> 13:24.434
Coming together, one man, one woman, coming together for the rest of their life

13:24.546 --> 13:31.377
to support, to love, to serve, to sacrifice for each other, purity and singleness, faithfulness in marriage.

13:31.477 --> 13:35.403
And this was seen to be radical in first century, unheard of.

13:36.965 --> 13:46.941
This is the days of gladiator fest where killing was seen as mere entertainment, but Christians embodied non-violence and forgiveness.

13:48.503 --> 13:50.226
You see, all the reasons.

13:50.466 --> 13:55.253
why they would be considered such a strange and weird group of people.

13:56.796 --> 14:00.241
It's because they had a whole different set of moral convictions.

14:01.323 --> 14:03.626
They were marching to a different drum beat.

14:03.646 --> 14:16.706
They had a different theological conviction than the rest of the world because they believed there were citizens of this new and better kingdom first, and participants of a Roman earthly empire second.

14:17.788 --> 14:19.410
So they lived distinct.

14:19.522 --> 14:24.228
set apart lives, and the church must do the same today.

14:25.429 --> 14:28.073
We cannot lower our standards to that of the world.

14:29.114 --> 14:40.068
We live above the fray, holding onto God's word, filled with his spirit, embodying God's character, his purpose, his kingdom on the earth.

14:40.088 --> 14:48.338
And when it comes to politics, we actually, as Christ followers, we have a different set of rules to live by than the rest of the world.

14:48.674 --> 14:53.620
And if you're not a Christ follower, I want to give you these five rules to call us into accountability to.

14:54.601 --> 15:00.829
Because Christians are church, we have a difference that are rules, norms that we live by.

15:01.169 --> 15:03.812
Five rules of engagement that I want to give us today.

15:04.733 --> 15:10.340
In our time together, from the Scriptures, from the New Testament, that sets us apart as kingdom citizens.

15:11.021 --> 15:12.763
Five rules that the rest of the world don't have.

15:13.344 --> 15:15.486
But you and I, we have from God's Word.

15:16.307 --> 15:18.610
First of all, that we are a

15:18.722 --> 15:20.024
prayerful people.

15:21.046 --> 15:26.093
The first rule of political engagement is prayer, and you might be thinking, what does prayer have anything to do with politics?

15:26.314 --> 15:29.438
Everything that we are prayerful.

15:30.300 --> 15:37.571
Notice what Paul said to young Timothy, as Paul is encouraging Timothy to contend for the faith, to run the race of faith well.

15:37.871 --> 15:44.722
Paul says in 1 Timothy, chapter 2, verse 1, I urge then, notice this, first of all,

15:45.346 --> 15:47.168
of high first importance.

15:47.268 --> 16:02.005
I am urging you, Timothy, first of all, that petitions, prayers, intercession, and thanksgiving be made for all people, for kings and all those in authority.

16:02.946 --> 16:05.829
You've heard Pastor Mark preach on this topic on this verse many times.

16:06.750 --> 16:11.015
And you've remembered maybe the who is king and emperor of this time.

16:11.635 --> 16:13.938
It's Nero, emperor Nero.

16:14.370 --> 16:19.797
One of the most evil, perverse, wicked emperors the world had ever seen.

16:21.500 --> 16:37.001
And yet, Paul has the audocities to say to Timothy, I need you, first of all, to pray for those in authority, for kings and all those in authority, not just for Nero, but all the other evil people like him.

16:38.763 --> 16:40.946
You might vehemently disagree with them.

16:41.154 --> 16:53.112
Think they are evil, they're doing everything wrong, and yet Paul's saying, I want you, first of all, to be a person, to be a church of prayer for those in authority.

16:54.515 --> 17:01.445
Notice that we are not instructed to pray about people, but to pray for them.

17:02.827 --> 17:07.154
You know, there's a whole lot of difference between praying about somebody and praying for them.

17:07.778 --> 17:11.644
And sometimes we tend to do a lot of praying about somebody, then praying for them.

17:11.664 --> 17:13.747
Here's what praying about somebody looks like.

17:14.448 --> 17:16.932
God, you and I already know I'm right.

17:18.294 --> 17:19.436
So just change their mind.

17:20.497 --> 17:22.921
Convince them how wrong they are.

17:23.301 --> 17:25.565
That's political venting, not prayer.

17:27.388 --> 17:28.910
But praying for somebody looks different.

17:29.210 --> 17:30.292
Praying for somebody.

17:30.933 --> 17:31.634
It says God.

17:31.746 --> 17:33.388
You make them in your image.

17:33.428 --> 17:34.330
They're loved by you.

17:34.350 --> 17:35.331
They're seen by you.

17:35.351 --> 17:36.713
They're known by you.

17:36.733 --> 17:37.855
Give them wisdom.

17:38.296 --> 17:39.377
Be with their family.

17:39.397 --> 17:43.083
They are a person who needs grace, who needs guidance.

17:43.123 --> 17:50.614
And so you get on your knees and you genuinely pray for somebody out of love and care for them.

17:50.674 --> 17:59.186
When you pray for people in politics, let me tell you what it does.

17:59.490 --> 18:05.096
When we pray for people in politics, it humanizes them instead of demonizing them.

18:06.898 --> 18:12.925
And there is such an easy temptation in all of us to demonize people, to quickly turn them into enemies.

18:13.225 --> 18:17.330
But when you pray for them, you realize they are a human being.

18:18.652 --> 18:23.817
That's a dad, that's a wife, that's a husband and mom, and that's a person.

18:25.119 --> 18:27.922
And you realize they're a person like you.

18:30.018 --> 18:50.258
Imagine what it would look like for your political engagement in all cases to begin with prayer, that if you gave yourself only permission to post about somebody after you prayed for them, that you would only publicly criticize somebody after you privately interceded for them.

18:51.138 --> 18:57.908
how different your posts would be, how different our tone would be if we genuinely prayed for them.

18:57.928 --> 19:00.111
I'm not saying, don't call people out.

19:00.631 --> 19:03.656
I'm not saying you can't call people out when they do wrong.

19:03.716 --> 19:14.090
You should, what I'm saying is that the first step of all of our engagement in the world, all of our political engagement is to be saturated in prayerfulness.

19:15.112 --> 19:16.454
We pray for, not about.

19:17.595 --> 19:19.538
Second of all, the second rule of engagement,

19:20.066 --> 19:22.749
is that we are a peaceful people, peaceful.

19:23.650 --> 19:25.812
The poll goes on, the poll goes on in this passage.

19:26.573 --> 19:36.684
Verse two, Prairie 4, Kings and all those in authority, that we may live peaceful and quiet lives in all godliness and holiness.

19:37.324 --> 19:46.514
This is good and pleases God our Savior who wants all people to be saved and to come to a knowledge of the truth.

19:47.522 --> 19:48.183
Here's some good news.

19:48.483 --> 19:55.492
When your political engagement is saturated in prayer, you can engage in politics without losing your peace.

19:56.593 --> 20:00.438
You can be a peaceful person in the midst of politics.

20:00.458 --> 20:00.698
Why?

20:01.079 --> 20:05.184
Because prayer gives you the right perspective of the world.

20:06.225 --> 20:09.149
Prayer puts everything into its right perspective.

20:09.950 --> 20:16.658
Prayer reminds you that God is on the throne and therefore you can be at peace.

20:17.314 --> 20:30.954
Prayer, just like in Isaiah 6, where Isaiah says, in the year King Uzziah died, King Uzziah, who had been on the throne of Israel for 52 years, has suddenly died, a closed companion of Isaiah.

20:31.394 --> 20:34.078
This is a time of political unrest in our people.

20:34.819 --> 20:45.234
But Isaiah says, in the year he died, in the year of great, unhevel, upheaval, and unrest, I saw the Lord seated on the throne.

20:45.634 --> 20:49.241
God was not pacing back and forth wondering what was going to happen.

20:49.481 --> 20:53.689
He was not wringing his hands concerned about who the next wood king would be.

20:53.969 --> 20:54.951
No, what was God doing?

20:55.191 --> 20:57.456
He was seated on the throne.

20:58.918 --> 21:03.186
And I got to tell you, you and I may be far more anxious about the next election than God is.

21:04.322 --> 21:07.086
He knows exactly the story he's writing.

21:07.266 --> 21:09.809
He is sovereign over the affairs of the universe.

21:10.110 --> 21:11.992
God knows what he's doing.

21:12.253 --> 21:26.211
And when we remind ourselves in prayer, who's really on the throne, a God who cannot be voted in or voted out, a God who can never be dethroned, a God sovereign over the affairs of the universe, you'll find yourself at peace.

21:27.453 --> 21:27.793
You do.

21:27.813 --> 21:32.199
So let me gently offer this to you.

21:33.321 --> 21:34.322
If politics

21:35.074 --> 21:37.438
is continually robbing you of your peace.

21:39.060 --> 21:40.903
You might have misplaced your trust.

21:43.667 --> 21:53.282
If your heart is always continually, continually anxious because of politics, you might have misplaced your source of hope.

21:55.425 --> 22:03.858
If your trust and your hope are in politics and in politicians, just for every two years, every four years, every time there's an election, your heart is on a roller coaster of fear and worry.

22:04.226 --> 22:05.768
Because politics always changes.

22:07.310 --> 22:18.186
But if your heart is fixed, trusting, hoping in Jesus alone, the Savior of the world, Lord of all, then your heart can live in a continual state of peace.

22:18.226 --> 22:18.506
Why?

22:19.067 --> 22:23.453
Because Jesus is the same yesterday, today, and forever.

22:23.813 --> 22:25.175
He never changes.

22:27.038 --> 22:29.962
So the state of your heart doesn't have to change.

22:30.863 --> 22:32.786
You can live at peace.

22:33.890 --> 22:40.718
That is what Paul says, when you live peaceful, even quiet lives in godliness and in holiness.

22:40.798 --> 22:44.042
Paul says, this actually pleases God.

22:45.224 --> 22:53.053
It pleases him, meaning your inner peace during a political tumultuous season is an act of worship.

22:53.994 --> 22:54.154
Why?

22:54.215 --> 22:55.676
Because it pleases God.

22:55.957 --> 22:58.219
It is an aroma of worship to God.

22:58.520 --> 23:00.402
One that pleases him.

23:00.738 --> 23:17.057
When the world is coming unhinged and no one knows what to do, the church is there continuing in peace, quietness, golliness, unholyness, and gosh, I find your worship to be so pleasing because your heart is fixated only on me.

23:19.200 --> 23:22.824
So the rules of engagement began with prayerfulness, peacefulness.

23:23.945 --> 23:28.210
The third rule of engagement is that we are prophetic as a church.

23:29.186 --> 23:34.471
While we are peaceful and prayerful, there's also a call for the church to be prophetic.

23:35.893 --> 23:47.304
And when I say prophetic, I'm not talking about predicting the future, but prophetic, I mean calling the world into right alignment with God's vision for the world.

23:48.425 --> 23:54.411
Calling people into accountability and alignment with God's vision, not your vision, but God's vision of the world.

23:54.712 --> 23:57.074
God's vision for righteousness.

23:57.410 --> 24:02.397
God's vision for justice, God's vision for the flourishing of all people.

24:02.457 --> 24:10.028
It is calling people into this vision alignment with the Lord about what God wants for the world.

24:11.250 --> 24:20.063
I believe this is what Jesus was referring to in Matthew 5 when he said these words to the church in verse 13, you are the salt of the earth.

24:21.164 --> 24:25.010
But if the salt shall lose its taste, how can it be made salty?

24:25.666 --> 24:29.832
is no longer good for anything but to be thrown out and trampled under people's feet.

24:30.814 --> 24:32.696
You are the light of the world.

24:32.716 --> 24:36.522
A city situated on a hill cannot be hidden.

24:38.104 --> 24:42.411
Light and salt can be preservatives and they're also proactive.

24:42.431 --> 24:45.155
Salt prevents a culture from further decay.

24:45.455 --> 24:48.339
It adds life and flavor and joy to the world.

24:49.762 --> 24:52.786
Light keeps people from stumbling in the dark.

24:53.314 --> 25:00.043
The church as the light of the world shows people who God is, his desire, his vision, his way for the world.

25:00.103 --> 25:02.566
We are salt and light.

25:02.687 --> 25:07.814
It describes the prophetic nature of the church of Jesus Christ.

25:08.935 --> 25:16.645
And across biblical narrative, what you find are men and women of God who carried this prophetic witness to their world.

25:16.946 --> 25:22.994
And oftentimes, it led them into direct engagement and interaction with the government of their day.

25:24.514 --> 25:34.127
So you think about Moses, who got a hold of God's vision for God's people, leading him directly into Pharaoh's chambers, declaring, let my people go.

25:34.187 --> 25:41.196
